{{Infobox writer <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].--> | name = Edward Arber | birth_date = 4 December 1836 | birth_place = London, England | death_date = 23 November 1912 | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = English academic and writer | language = English | nationality = British | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = <!-- or: | genres = --> | subject = <!-- or: | subjects = --> | movement = | notableworks = *A Transcript of the Registers of the Stationers' Company * The Term Catalogues, 1668-1709/11.[2] | spouse = Married in 1869 | partner = <!-- or: | partners = --> | children = Two children including E. A. N. Arber | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} '''Edward Arber''' (4 December 1836 – 23 November 1912<ref>''Who's Who 1914''</ref>) was an [[England|English]] scholar, writer, and editor.
[[File:Mason Science College.png|thumb|right|[[Mason Science College|Mason College, now Birmingham University]]]]
==Background and professional work== Arber was born in [[London]]. From 1854 he 1878 he worked as a clerk in the [[Admiralty]], and began evening classes at [[King's College London]] in 1858. From 1878 to 1881 he studied English literature, under H. Morley, at [[University College London]]; and from 1881 to 1894 he was professor of English at [[Mason College]] (which later became [[Birmingham University]]). From 1894 he lived in London as emeritus professor, being also a fellow of [[King's College London]]. In 1905 he received the honorary degree of D. Litt. from the [[University of Oxford]]. He married in 1869, and had two sons, one of whom, [[Edward Alexander Newell Arber|E. A. N. Arber]], became demonstrator in [[paleobotany]] at the [[University of Cambridge]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
==Scholarly edits== As a scholarly editor, Arber made notable contributions to [[English literature]]. His name is associated particularly with the series of "[[English Reprints]]" (1868–1871), by which an accurate text of the works of many English authors, formerly only accessible in more expensive editions, was placed within reach of the general public. Among the thirty volumes of the series were [[Stephen Gosson]]'s ''School of Abuse'', [[Roger Ascham]]'s ''[[Toxophilus]]'', ''[[Tottel's Miscellany]]'', and [[Robert Naunton]]'s ''Fragmenta Regalia''. It was followed by the "English Scholar's Library" (16 volumes) which included the ''Works'' (1884) of [[John Smith of Jamestown|Captain John Smith]], governor of [[Virginia]], and the ''Poems'' (1882) of [[Richard Barnfield]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
==Other publications== In his ''English Garner'' (8 vols. 1877-1890) he collected rare old tracts and poems; in 1899-1901 he issued ''[[British Anthologies]]'', and in 1907 began a series called ''[[A Christian Library]]''. He was also the sole editor of two vast English bibliographies: ''A Transcript of the [[Stationers' Register|Registers of the Stationers' Company]]'', 1553-1640 (1875–1894), and ''[[Term Catalogue|The Term Catalogues]]'', 1668-1709/11.<ref>''The Term Catalogues, 1668-1709, With a Number for Easter Term, 1711 A.D. A Contemporary Bibliography of English Literature in the Reigns of Charles II, James II, William and Mary, and Anne.'' Ed. by Edward Arber, vols. 1-3. London: Edward Arber, 1903/ 1905/ 1906.</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}} ;Attribution {{EB1911|wstitle=Arber, Edward|volume=2 }}
